body:
Right now as much as 5G is ready to roll out, it isn’t.


It still needs to be tried and tested... and tested again, and again and again and again in a virtual environment.


The companies heavily involved in this are engineering simulation companies like ANSYS and Siemens who have PLM products that are heavily integrated into the R&D strategy of major 5G OEM Manufactures like Qualcomm.


I would go long on ANSYS and Qualcomm if you want some risk-free exposure to 5G.

India needs to get over its divisive politics and high levels of corruption and red tape to take advantage of this opportunity. There is a reason why Walmart is yet to realize any benefit despite significant investments.

The government has done nothing to supplement incomes for their citizens despite a huge population not having a steady job. The last time the government got some money in its coffers, it spend most of it building huge statues of political leaders.

US and other importers will need to be more cognizant of where they want to shift their supply chains.  India has its own set of major issues and non-inclusive policies by Modi are definitely not helping their case.

author: andrejandre
body: Perhaps people should realize that Robinhood is new Fintech. It's geared powerfully towards casual long-term investors. My use of the word casual really means those who *do not really care to become experts at finance and investing on a trading platform*. I feel like it has the potential to be a robust platform for time-sensitive trading, but it feels a bit too infant for that. I love using it for holding, DRIP, or longer term swing trades. Honestly, I give RH 5 stars for my personal use. But, if you're in that boat of people who has $25k+ and don't want to get marked as a pattern day trader, I'd try to be cognizant of the tech and culture behind the platform as well. Give RH time, and those time-sensitive nightmares may be ironed out.

author: dgmiller81
body:
Amazon didn't anticipate everything that was coming along with it.   Many companies had increased their AWS platforms and expanded their infrastructure to support work from home and home users.    Big players like Netflix expanded their infrastructure on AWS in large numbers to accommodate the increased traffic.    Thinking that Amazon stock was going to tank isn't good sense.  

What I expect is that tech companies will start to drop when more layoffs occur in the big business sector.  Small business isn't where tech is making money, they are making it off of the big corporations.   I bought up F5 (FFIV) as much a week or two before their earnings.   Not because of them selling more hardware (more expense, less margin) but based solely of how many corporations had to increase their VPN licenses (minimal overhead and high margin).   This was  a good tech play.   I made off pretty with that one.  I also expect their earnings to tank in Q2 because people will expect them to be high again, but corporations have already purchased licenses to accommodate.   Now they are screwed for probably the next year for licenses alone.   Stock will start to drop because of that.   

Tech sector is an interesting one.   Unless I know about the technology and what drives it up/down I don't play in it.   I understood AWS and FFIV working in IT.   Just my two cents.

author: carolina0000FFs
body: You can also trade index funds on Robinhood by purchasing ETFs. However, Robinhood is a less mature investment platform. It's popular with people just getting started, but it has had a lot of bugs and outages and lacks good features for long term investing (like support for IRAs). Robinhood has been popular for a while because they popularized free trades and a good app. While the latter is subjective, most major brokerages have free trades and apps now. Fidelity is my choice which works well for index funds or individual stocks.

author: Zeddicus11
body: I started out with Robinhood, but then switched to Fidelity because their platform is more stable and developed, also offers mutual funds, allows opening a Roth IRA and checking account besides just a brokerage account, offers a great credit card etc. They also reimbursed me for the $75 Robinhood charged me to transfer all my stocks. RH seems great for relatively low stakes and experimenting with day trading in their nice looking app, whereas Fidelity (and Vanguard, and many other brokers) are more meant to be for long term investing and saving for retirement, rather than for day trading.
